<h2 class="section-title">The Fort Kochi Photography Guide</h2>
<p>
  Fort Kochi is a visual wonderland. From weathered colonial plaster and towering green trees to silent backwaters and active fishing harbors, every corner feels like a film set. Here is my curated guide to getting the best shots:
</p>

<div class="safety-grid" style="margin-top: 2rem;">
  
  <div class="safety-card" style="border-top: 3px solid var(--sunset-light);">
    <h4><i class="fa-solid fa-camera"></i> Top 5 Instagram Spots</h4>
    <ul style="padding-left: 1.25rem; color: var(--text-medium); font-size: 0.95rem;">
      <li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><strong>Loafer's Corner (Princess Street):</strong> The classic intersection featuring the vintage bright-yellow Dutch-style building.</li>
      <li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><strong>Chinese Fishing Nets at Sunset:</strong> Capture the giant nets silhouetted against a golden and purple sky.</li>
      <li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><strong>Princess Street Bicycles:</strong> Old black commuter bicycles parked against peeling colonial plaster walls.</li>
      <li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><strong>Jew Town Spice Warehouses:</strong> Colorful wooden doors and giant antique copper vessels lining the pathways.</li>
      <li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><strong>Kashi Art Café:</strong> The narrow entrance hallway filled with striking contemporary art installations.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="safety-card" style="border-top: 3px solid var(--sunset-light);">
    <h4><i class="fa-solid fa-clock"></i> Golden Hour & Timings</h4>
    <p>
      The sunlight in Kochi can be harsh and glaring between 10:30 AM and 3:30 PM. For warm, soft lighting:
    </p>
    <ul style="padding-left: 1.25rem; color: var(--text-medium); font-size: 0.95rem;">
      <li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><strong>Sunrise (6:00 AM – 7:15 AM):</strong> Head to the Vypin Island jetty or Marine Drive. The water is calm and mist rises off the channels.</li>
      <li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><strong>Sunset (5:30 PM – 6:30 PM):</strong> Sit on the Fort Kochi beachfront seawall or Vasco da Gama Square promenade.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="safety-card" style="border-top: 3px solid var(--sunset-light);">
    <h4><i class="fa-solid fa-helicopter"></i> Drone Regulations</h4>
    <p>
      <strong>Important Warning:</strong> Fort Kochi is situated adjacent to critical naval, defense, and shipyard zones. Kochi Harbor and the shipyard are strictly **No-Fly Zones** for civilian drones. Do not attempt to fly drones near the harbor mouth, shipping lanes, or navy offices. You risk confiscation of equipment and legal action. For other areas, standard DGCA rules apply (register on DigitalSky).
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="safety-card" style="border-top: 3px solid var(--sunset-light);">
    <h4><i class="fa-solid fa-lightbulb"></i> My Best Shooting Tips</h4>
    <ul style="padding-left: 1.25rem; color: var(--text-medium); font-size: 0.95rem;">
      <li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><strong>Street portraits:</strong> Locals are generally happy to pose. Always smile, show them your camera, and ask, "Chetta, photo?" (Brother, photo?) or "Chechi, photo?" (Sister, photo?).</li>
      <li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><strong>Peeling textures:</strong> Set your exposure compensation slightly lower to bring out the rich, wet, mossy textures of the old brick walls.</li>
      <li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><strong>Protect your gear:</strong> The salty ocean air can leave a fine film on your camera lenses. Carry microfibre cloths and keep a UV filter on your lens.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

</div>
